Aug 1,  2021 Started making new handle for my toothing plane. Fitted it, but not chamfered and rounded the grip yet.
Aug 2,  2021 Completed and fitted the new handle for the toothing plane. Marked out piece to cut for the new high angle plane body. Not the mouth etc, only the crosscut. Cutting it at a slight angle as the body will not run parallel to the original sides of the beam so it follows the grain better.
Aug 3,  2021 Cut the piece for the body of the high angle plane. Handle of toothing plane was coming loose whenever I removed the blade so I glued it in. Prepared the face side at some cost. This stuff is very hard.
Aug 5,  2021 Prepared face edge of high angle plane body. Toothing plane is working nicely and new handle is now secure. Marked out bed and mouth.
Aug 6,  2021 Drilled and rough cut the mouth of the high angle jack plane.
Aug 7,  2021 Cleaned up the mouth and rough fitted the blade with temporary wedges. Cuts very nicely, although it jams quickly because the  mouth still needs refinement.
Aug 8,  2021 Made the wedge and refined the mouth. Cuts very well and made short work of planing the offcut from its body.
Aug 9,  2021 Cut out the tote for the high angle jack plane, including sawing to thickness with the kerfing plane and big rip, plus drill and coping saw followed by spokeshave.
Aug 10, 2021 Shaped and fitted the tote, cleaned up the top surface of the high angle jack plane body.
Aug 11, 2021 Finished off the high angle jack plane. Added chamfers and cleaned up all the surfaces. glued in the handle. Sanded some more and oiled it.
Aug 12, 2021 Prepared the face side of one of the lathe bedways. Started to work on the face edge. New plane is working well although it still needs to be sharpened frequently. Pretty sure that is just because of the extreme hardness of the timber.
Aug 13, 2021 Bit more work on the face edge, but back was hurting so I didn't push it. Cleaned up the toothing plane handle, and oiled it, and the new plane (with Pony's help)
Aug 14, 2021 Nailed in the edging strips in the toolchest lid.
Aug 15, 2021 Drawing plans for the frame joints of the lathe.
Aug 16, 2021 Decided to use the opposite face of the lathe bedways as the face side to maximize the amount of the heart that gets kept. Started truing that up. Multiple sharpenings, lots of adjusting practice. I think the trick to dealing with ultra hard woods is being able to resharpen quickly and efficiently. Showed Pony how to feel for a burr when sharpening, and how to look along a plane to see the set, or a piece to see the curve..
Aug 17, 2021 Taking it easy today. Showed Pen how to mark out the stock for her dolls house bed.
Aug 18, 2021 Back to trying to prep the stock for the bedways of the lathe. 5 cuts and the plane loses its edge. About 20 and it wont cut any more. Got the new face side done and started on the edge. Using the toothing plane as well now. The edge lasts a bit longer but still not all that long.
Aug 19, 2021 Completed face edge and marked out the thickness. 1/8 - 3/16 to remove from one end. Not sure whether to use the kerfing-plane (or plough plane) followed by a large gouge or use the scrub plane. It probably doesn't warrant the adze.
Aug 20, 2021 Roughed the first bedway to thickness with the scrub plane. Cuts well into the sapwood, but struggles with the heartwood as expected. Finished it off with the toothing plane. Modified the toothing plane handle. It's not as pretty but seems more comfortable now.
Aug 22, 2021 Made and fitted supports for the T-square in the tool chest.
Aug 23, 2021 More work on the first bedway face side and edge. Pretty close now.
Aug 24, 2021 Started on the second bedway. Got the face side roughly flat and started on the face edge.
Aug 25, 2021 More work on the face edge. It was quite curved, needed to remove about 1/4inch. Used the adzes.
Aug 28, 2021 More work on the face side. There is still a slight twist but its close to done.
Aug 29, 2021 Started work on making Bergeron readable. The English translation only covers volume 1 so I'm attempting to translate the French using the fulltext from archive.org and google translate. This is going to take a while. The OCR is good but there is a lot of crap in there that needs to be removed and formatted sensibly. Using org to assist this.
Aug 31, 2021 More work on the face side and edge of the second lathe bedway. Face is close enough now, started cutting the kerf to saw it to width. Cut a new piece (1inch thick) for the kerfing saw so I can use it to cut the bedways to depth. Still need to finish it. Rearranged the bottom layer of the toolchest so the kerfing saw can be accessible, and put away when it is set to a large width. Now most of the planes run front to back and the kerfing plane lives in front of the carving tools box.
Sep 1,  2021 Finished the kerf and started sawing. Painfully slow and constantly sticking. Started sharpening the saw (big rip) and ended up reshaping the teeth to have a bit less of an aggressive angle.
Sep 2,  2021 Finished sharpening the saw and completed the cut. The saw didn't need resetting. Much easier when it's sharp. Not sure if the less aggressive angle has made much difference. I suspect the cut is slightly slower, but easier and more predictable. That's a combination of guesswork, wishful thinking, and maybe the tiniest bit of immeasurable feel. Whatever. It's working well, even in this extremely hard wood.
Sep 6,  2021 Sharpened both spokeshaves. Also managed to wear away my r.middle finger nail. I keep forgetting abrasives can do this...
Sep 8,  2021 More work on cleaning up the raw text for the Bergeron book.
Sep 14, 2021 Flattened the newly sawn face of the back bedway. This will be the final face side, and the internal edge of the bedway slot.
Sep 16, 2021 finished preparing the final face sides and edges for the bedways. Used the high angle jack.I can sharpen and set it a lot quicker now. Also getting in to the habit of sharpening it before putting it away. Makes starting off the next day much easier. Also started cutting the kerf for the depth cut on the back bedway. It's too close to the edge to saw but will serve as a guideline for using the scrub plane..
Sep 17, 2021 Started cutting the kerf for the depth cut on the front bedway. Hard going. The kerfing plane does a good job, but it often seems to be a bit of a fight. Maybe that is why there is no evidence of them being used historically. They can compensate for a lack of skill in rip sawing accurately, but maybe the best way is just to practice.
Sep 18, 2021 Cut the kerf a little deeper but not to full depth. The saw is way easier to use. Cut the excess off. Tried the high angle jack plane out on a 2in square section piece with wild grain. Very little tearout is visible. There is still some, but nothing that would cause a problem.
Sep 25, 2021 Planed the last edge of the bedways. Ready to start building the frame now.
Sep 28, 2021 Started to sort out stock for the lathe frame. Nothing cut yet, I need to decide if I should use the thicker piece for the 2 front uprights. There is just enough, but then it doesn't match at the bottom end, so it will need shaping. It's either that or have less thickness for the bedway Holtzapffel dovetail joints. Both options are possible.
