Dec 25, 2021 Bought a metal turning lathe, and started to clean it up. Dismantled the cross slide and reassembled it.
Dec 26, 2021 dismantled and reassembled the top slide. Recut some of the threads on the toolpost which have seen some abuse. The handwheel on the top slide had the wrong screw holding the wheel with the graduations in place. The threads are a different pitch from usual, so although the replacement screw was the correct size (6mm) it had messed up the threads. I redrilled it and cut a thread the next size up as I had an allen headed screw of the right size. The head was too wide so I used the lathe to turn it down to roughly match the original on the other handwheel. 2 different sized screws turned by the same allen key now. 
Dec 27, 2021 Finished cleaning up the threads in the toolpost. They are all ok now, although there aren't enough bolts for all of them. 2 of the tapped holes had pieces of broken bolt in them. The first came out yesterday, pushed by the tap (I didn't realise it was there) The second I drilled as close as I could get to the correct tapping size then cut the remains out with the tap. The taps I have are a cheap set but they seem to be holding up well. Unfortunately I can't say the same for the tap driver which appears to be made of cheese. Wish I could find the old tap driver I had. Simple square holes in a hardened steel bar are far more sensible than a fancy adjusting mechanism with left and right hand threads.
