Oct 5,  2022 Cut the notches in the bar clamp. Shaped the sliding piece and drilled it. Rounded the end of the 2 straps. Put the bar clamp together.
Oct 6,  2022 Added the feet to the bar clamp. Needed a 12mm drill for the insert in the rotating foot and the one I bought from the local hardware shop turned out to be bent. I tried to straighten it, probably doomed to failure with an HSS bit. Sure enough it shattered leaving me with just enough to sharpen. Now it is tiny but it cuts perfectly.
Oct 7,  2022 New 6mm tap and die arrived. Cut the threads to finish of the metalwork and oiled the clamp.
Oct 9,  2022 Cleaned up the joints of the 4th 5th and 6th sections of the wheel rim and glued them together. Rough prepped the bar for a second bar clamp.
Oct 10, 2022 Cleaned up the joints of the 7th 8th and 9th sections of the wheel rim and glued them together. Sharpened the medium rip saw.
Oct 11, 2022 Cleaned up the joints of the 10th 11th and 12th sections and glued them.
Oct 12, 2022 Cut the curve on the inside edge of the 1,2,3 piece of the wheel rim. Bendy plane works nicely. Back twinge so I stopped at the first piece.
Oct 13, 2022 Cut the inside curves on the other 3 pieces of the wheel rim and started to fit the joint between the first 2
Oct 14, 2022 Fitted the remaining joints and refined the inside curve a little. 
Oct 15, 2022 Cut the curve in the rebate of 2 sections of the wheel rim. Decided I need a compass shoulder plane to refine the rebates.
Oct 16, 2022 Started making a compass shoulder plane. Trying to glue things without location in tricky. Next time I will use a pin of some sort. Glued on the second side later in the day. Used some blocks clamped (dry) to the body to help align the slippery glued piece, removing them once the main clamps were tight enough to stop the glued piece sliding about.
Oct 17, 2022 Completed the compass shoulder plane and got it tuned to cut nicely. Cleaned up 2 of the wheel rim pieces.
Oct 18, 2022 Drilled and cut the curve in the rebate on the remaining 2 wheel rim pieces. Roughly cleaned them up with the new plane. Need to close up about a 1inch gap. I think about half of this will go when I finish cleaning up the last pieces. Then will need to deepen the curved surface on the widest to completely close the gap.
Oct 19, 2022 Cleaned up the inside curve of piece 3. Gap is down to about 3/4 inch
Oct 20, 2022 Cleaned up inside curve of piece 4. Gap is down to about 3/8 inch
Oct 21, 2022 More cleanup. Gap is now down to 1/8 inch.
Oct 22, 2022 Started cleaning up the side face of the recess, also taking a little off the inner face. Surface is now almost flat and the gap is almost gone. Still need to do a bit of adjusting on some of the joints. Brass wingnuts arrived and I re-did the point and pencil holder with Pony's help.
Oct 23, 2022 More cleanup of the joints between the 3 piece sections. Managed to break on of the glue joints. Looks like it was a bit starved. Reglued it and also glued the first 2 of the 3 piece sections together to make a half circle. Will need to treat it gently until the overlapping pieces of the second layer are added.
Oct 24, 2022 More joint cleanup. Glued the other 2 three piece sections together. Flattened the face of the first 6 part section.
Oct 25, 2022 Started to cut the outside curve of the first 3 piece section of the wheel. Hard going, might just wait till I can turn it. Flattened the face of the 2nd 3 piece section of the flywheel. Added a shim to the joint between section 12 and section 1 where I had cut too much away.
Oct 26, 2022 More fitting. Broke one of the joints again. Not enough clamps to glue that and glue the 2 6 part sections together at the same time. Went out and bought 6 more clamps and an angle grinder to finish off the metalwork. Glued the sections together.
Oct 27, 2022 Removed the flywheel/pulley from the glued up sections and used the wire brush attachment in the angle grinder to clean it up.
Oct 28, 2022 Started grinding off the rough patches on the flywheel/pulley.
Oct 29, 2022 More grinding. Lots of sneezing, I guess I'm reacting to the fine iron particles.
Oct 30, 2022 Made a makeshift stand so I can rotate the wheel without having to lift it out of the metalwork vice and turn it. The front section of the vice had to pass between 2 spokes in order to grip the boss. In theory this is simple, but in practice lifting 23Kg of wheel and manoeuvering it to just the right angle is a pain. The stand is just a beam with a hole near the end and a bolt to hang the wheel on. This should make finishing off the wheel a lot easier. 
Oct 31, 2022 More grinding. Sometimes the dust from grinding cast iron turns my skin orange. I guess it must be rust...
Nov 1,  2022 Went to visit Tuan and asked him what was the best paint for cast iron. Came away with some 2 part black paint to use.
Nov 2,  2022 More work on the flywheel, this time with files. They work quite well where the surface has been removed.
Nov 3,  2022 Back to using the angle grinder, now doing the faces of the arms of the flywheel and the outer rim.
Nov 4,  2022 Just cleaning today. Black dust everywhere. Now have a tin full of iron. Collected using a magnet inside a plastic bag.
Nov 5,  2022 Painted the wheel. Great paint, didn't expect it to be matt. Dries fast but the mixed stuff seems to last.
Nov 6,  2022 Cleaned up the floor scraper the decorators left. Tightened the head and painted it. Planed the face side of the next piece of the beam that will become the other face of the wheel. Painted the toolrest.
Nov 7,  2022 Painted the inside of the slot in the toolrest. Mixed paint is still usable. Cut a kerf for the 7/8inch plank for some of the face sections of the wheel. Started to saw it. Stopped to sharpen the saw. Cuts almost twice as fast now. Got about 2/3 of the way down the plank.
Nov 8,  2022 Completed the saw cut. Made a bracket to hang the coping saw in the front of the chest. Cut a kerf for a 1/4inch plank which will remove the part damaged by nails leaving enough to cut another 7/8 inch plank for the remaining outer sections of the flywheel.
Nov 9,  2022 Cut the 1/4inch plank and the 7/8inch plank. First was easy, second a bit more tricky because the cut came to the surface. This tends to make the cut wander outwards leaving something to plane off. Considering the best way to handle this. No conclusions yet. Tried to put the cast iron wheel back into the wooden rim. It didn't want to fit so I removed it again.
Nov 10, 2022 Cleaned up the inside of the wooden rim and got the cast iron wheel back in again. Manoeuvring it is tricky and painful. Also managed to break one of the joints. Should be easy enough to glue up again once the outer layer piece over that joint goes on.Started to make a plug for the centre of the wheel boss to locate the compass point. This was tricky as it needed to be 40mm and the maximum that the metal turning lathe can take is around 25mm. Ended up using the headstock shaft and a cupchuck from the old lathe with the crosslide and a metal turning tool serving as a back centre. Made a temporary toolrest from a block of wood, a threaded insert and a piece of angle iron. The iron didn't want to be drilled.
Nov 11, 2022 Heated up the iron on the cooker and sharpenned the drill bits I blunted on it yesterday. Made the hole and completed the toolrest. Very carefully turned the plug. Layed out the screw holes on the wooden rim.
Nov 12, 2022 Drilled all 48 holes by hand. Made some pins to mark the holes in the outer pieces from the holes in the existing rim. Cut the first 2 outer pieces and fitted them over the broken joint and the one next to it. Near disaster when I tried to use the brace to drive a screw and it sheared off. Managed to drill most of it out. Thread extractor didn't work as expected but seems to have pushed the remainingbrass outwards enough to allow a new screw to pass and bite in the wood below it. Thankfully the screw broke before it was close to fully home. Not entirely happy with the hole placement. I should have left more room at the end with the upper part of the half lap. Not going to redrill all 48 holes unless I have to. I think there is more than enough glue area for strength.
Nov 13, 2022 Glued up the separated joint and added the corresponding outer piece. Continued adding outer pieces and got half way round the wheel before running out of glue. Put some on to soak ready for tomorrow. Started planing how I might use the electric router to remove some of the waste once the wheel is all glued up. I don't much like the thing, too noisy, but it will probably help if the flywheel is almost round befor I try turning it.
Nov 14, 2022 Made up the new batch of glue and added 4 more pieces. Only 2 to go.
Nov 15, 2022 Glued the last 2 pieces of the flwheel rim. Found a piece to make the router arm guide.
Nov 16, 2022 Made up a guide for the router and rounded off one side of the flywheel. The other is already partially done with the compass plane. Might round it a little more with the saw and compass plane, but it's probably ok to just turn it at this point. 
Nov 17, 2022 Clean up and dismantle the lathe frame to add the bearing support extensions. Start prepping a piece for the extensions.
Nov 18, 2022 resaw the piece for the bearing support extensions. Rough cut both pieces.
Nov 19, 2022 Finish shaping the bearing support extensions and glue and screw them in place.
Nov 20, 2022 Cut the bearing mounting surface to be parallel to the outer surface of the frame, ie coplanar with the extension pieces.
Nov 21, 2022 Put the lathe frame back together and fitted the shaft and flywheel. It turns reasonably freely although there is a slight scraping at one point. Loosening the bearing mount at the right hand side reveals that it is trying to move backwards at one point which implies the shaft is not quite parallel to the axis of the left hand bearings rotation. It's not far off and hopefully will wear in. There is a lot of momentum in the wheel... Considering using the saw horse as a freestanding tool rest support to turn the wheel.
Nov 22, 2022 Mostly planing what to do next. Considering redesigning the headstock so the thread guides are to the right of the pulley so I can have the flywheel as far to the left as possible. Hung the dragon up, and figured out how to dismantle Dad's old parker 51. The breather tube was blocked  so it wouldn't fill. Had to use the hairdryer to heat it up around the metal band area to get the nib cover to unscrew. Also used some strands of wire to poke at the dried ink in the breather tube. Seems to work ok now. Re-alligning the nib was a bit fiddly. Have to unscrew the cover section to move it around so it lines up with the cover section when it is tghtened. Got it on about the 4th go.
Nov 23, 2022 Cleaned up and sharpened my turning tools.
Nov 24, 2022 Trying to find a piece for the headstock. Planed the face of the 5x5 I sit on at the drill press. Might do the job depending on how bad the crack is.
Nov 25, 2022 Drawing possible designs for the headstock. Would like to keep the flywheel as far to the left as possible and the Bergeron style screw cutting headstock would push it a long way to the right.
Nov 26, 2022 More drawing. Also started trying to print out the APL book.
