Jan 8,  2024 Sorted through some of the extreme hardwood looking for pieces for a walking stick flute. I think this is higher priority than the Hotteterre.
Jan 9,  2024 Cut up a piece of stone rosewood that started as 3½in x 1½in. Thought long and hard about how to get a decent piece out of it avoiding holes on one edge and sapwood on the other. Gave up on the idea of getting 2 1½ in square pieces as that would have meant the only long piece had significant sapwood. Went for a slightly narrower piece with sapwood that will be fine for tool handles.
Jan 10, 2024 Drawing plans for a flute stick. I think I like the one based around a 3 piece design (actually 5 pieces counting the handle and spike).
Jan 11, 2024 Drilled the longest piece of Stone Rosewood. The drill came out off centre and with a curved bore but it should be ok. The D bit drill works well and I think I will try making a longer one from some of the smooth rebar I bought. The old bits cut ok but at least one of them needs the end re-making. Also there is not much room for sharpening with that design (end drilled out and cut to a U channel and then a slit made a short way down and the ends folded in) The design is good but I doubt it is worth the effort involved. I will see how a D bit handles long holes. Also thinking about rough reamers. I don't like the bent handle of the ½inch rough reamer and the thick section means it has a very negative cutting angle. I might regrind it so one face is on the diameter and only 2 edges cut rather than all 4 as per Jan Boertse's recommendations. Might just make a new one. The rough reamer is useful for correcting the curve in the bore I think. Maybe I should just start with a larger hole?
Jan 12, 2024 Machined the end of the ½inch long drill for a new handle. Started trying to make an 8mm thread but the drill is harder than the cheap die. Turned it down further and cut a 6mm thread on the end.
Jan 13, 2024 Turned a handle for the ½inch drill. Started to file the tail end of the drill square.
Jan 14, 2024 Finished off the square end on the ½inch drill and squared the mortice in the handle to fit.
Jan 15, 2024 Drilled the body section of the walking stick flute out to ½inch. The hole is now more central than it was with the original ¼inch hole. There is plenty wood left. Lesson: Smaller bits bend and can produce a curved hole. Most of the long drills I have do not leave a reliable centre to start a smaller hole at the bottom of a larger one. It may be necessary to do this so I need to consider how to locate the smaller drill inside the larger hole. Step drills or sleeves on a smaller drill are possibilities.
Jan 16, 2024 Reamed the body section. It is not complete, but making progress. The wood is finishing nicely. I will need to make some more reamers to complete it. The older of the 2 finish reamers is too steeply tapered and the newer one, although closer, is cracked and not really up to removing several mm. Reaming the whole length is too much anyway. The reamers seem to cut better when working on a shorter length. Ordered some 3mm HSS to make some new reamer blades, and a couple of 300mm long 14mm drills.
Jan 17, 2024 Cut a clean section from a badly cracked, warped, and worm eaten beam to make a morse taper holder so I can use the tailstock chuck from the metal lathe to hand drill flute bodies in the new lathe. Trued it up and cut to dimensions for turning. Also cut some notches to help the transition from round to rectangular. I can do this on the lathe but it is easy to split away the corners so this might make it safer.
Jan 18, 2024 Finished turning the morse taper handle and started making the steel plate to locate the end of the shaft.
Jan 19, 2024 Finished the locating plate and fitted it to the handle.
Jan 20, 2024 Started work on the reamer driver. Turned down some 14mm bar and cut a 10mm thread. Started filing the section below the thread into a square.
Jan 21, 2024 Finished squaring the driver shaft and cut the slot. Still needs widening a bit.
Jan 22, 2024 Finished cutting the slot and drilled and tapped the holes for the grub screws. Still need to straighten the slot and harden it.
Jan 23, 2024 Sawed 2 20inch sides of a 1½ inch square from the same badly worm eaten baulk as the morse taper holder. Turned drilled and morticed the handle for the reamer driver. Hardened the steel part and assembled it all.
Jan 24, 2024 Ground a piece of 18x3x200 HSS to a taper for the top end of the body piece of a 3 piece flute, based on the measurements from Ardal Powells article on the Hotettere flutes. 18mm to 16mm over 200mm. (Probably good for the left hand piece of a 4 piece flute too)
Jan 26, 2024 Started making the long reamer holder. Turned and threaded the end and sawed the square. Using the hacksaw was fiddly, but probably saved me a day of filing. The offcuts were less than 1mm thick.
Jan 27, 2024 Finished the square end of the long reamer holder and made and fittesd a handle.
Jan 28, 2024 Cut the slot in the end of the long reamer holder. Using a piece of HSS as a cold chisel works quite well, although I don't think grinding it at an angle helped much. Both edges still cut, even though one had a significantly negative cutting angle.
Jan 29, 2024 Drilled and tapped the holes for the grub screws in the long reamer holder. Started grinding the 14mm-16mm reamer blade.
Jan 30, 2024 Completed the 14-16 reamer blade and hardened the long handle end.
Jan 31, 2024 Used the 2 new reamers to rough finish the centre joint bore of the flute stick. I say "rough" as in not done. The surface is pretty smooth, just perhaps a little more to be removed once I cut the piece to its final length.
Feb 2,  2024 Cut the headjoint piece to lengthand set it up for drilling.
Feb 3,  2024 Made a 10mm d-bit.
Feb 4,  2024 Drilled the headjoint. Hardened and tempered the 10mm bit. It was working but seemed to need a lot of pressure. This was improved by grinding the top surface. I think this is due to the size of the remaining part of the circle rather than the very slight cutting angle created by the curve of the grinding wheel. Although it cuts better now I may take a little more off. I don't think it should require much pressure to make it cut. The hole in the headjoint was pretty accurate. Not easy to measure but I think it was about 0.4mm off centre at the exit end, over a length of around 320mm.
Feb 5,  2024 Bored the headjoint out using the 2 flat drills. It's now around 17mm. Looks like the sequence will be 10mm D-bit to establish a good pilot hole followed by 14mm and 17mm flat bits. 12mm twist bits may also be useful but the home made bits with the folded over ends will probably be retired or recut as d-bits. They were an attempt to make a shell bit substitute and although they worked reasonably well I think easy sharpening is important and they soon sharpen to nothing plus they don't offer much, if anything, over d-bits.
Feb 6,  2024 Rounded off the wide end of the 16mm-18mm reamer and put it through the headjoint.
Feb 16, 2024 Cut a piece of wood for the new carrier. Drilled it most of the way through at 2⅛in and used the hole to mount it on the lathe. Started to turn out the recess for the bearing.
Feb 17, 2024 Completed the recess for the bearing and cut some strips of steel to hold it in place.
Feb 18, 2024 Turned the face of the bearing support block, trimmed the lower end so the bearing lines up with the lathe centres, and cut the recesses for the metal retaining plates.
Feb 19, 2024 Drilled the holes in the bearing mounting block and fitted the retainers and the 2 countersink inserts.
Mar 4,  2024 Made the front rail for the keyboard stand.
Apr 8,  2024 Finished reshaping the dovetails saw handle.
