May 12, 2024 Drawing up plans for a flute can after Naust E:710
May 16, 2024 Made an 18-20 tapered reamer blade. Reamed the head joint and the body out to approximately the correct size.
May 18, 2024 Drew an exaggerated bore profile ready for fine adjustments of the reamers/bore.
May 22, 2024 Selected a piece of scrap for a carrier for the body of the new flute.
May 23, 2024 Turned taper on the carrier. I had misjudged the length, it was too short. Found another piece and turned a taper on it. Still a bit large, the flute section doesn't go all the way on yet. Both pieces had a nail in them that wasn't obvious to the eye. Removed them by turning down either side leaving a rough bead containing the nail, then cut away a bit of the bead so I could get hold of the nail with the pincers.
May 24, 2024 Completed the carrier for the flute body.
May 25, 2024 Turned the outside of the flute body so it is concentric with the bore. Still oversize.
May 27, 2024 Added a reinforcing wire to the square cup chuck. Turned some of the remaining old cup chucks to fit the brass cup chuck, including the small square cup chuck.
May 28, 2024 Turned 2 plug centres, 20mm and 20.3mm
May 29, 2024 Made a plug chuck for the headjoint. Turned the outside of the headjoint. Its about 36mm now.
May 30, 2024 Turned a piece for the joint between the head and body of the flute. Drilled a hole through it, up to 17.5mm using various drill bits. Finished off with the mt4 17.5. It was grabbing badly so I reground it to have less of an angle. Also reground some old long flat drills. It looks like the simple D bits are the best and I will probably make at least one more, a 14mm. Regrinding the 10mm I managed to mess up the grinding wheel. It's probably not a good idea to leave the bit in the heavy hand chuck as it bounced and dinged the wheel. Spent some time tweaking the grinder and it is working ok but would benefit from dressing the wheels.
Jun 1,  2024 Started work on the Burns faceplate. I think I can see how to make it work. Cut a piece of scrap steel for a reinforcing plate and marked out a piece of ebony to replace the broken corner. The fretboard is very worn and there is not much of the frets left. I will put it together and try it out, I always did like the low frets. If it has buzzing problems I guess it will be time for a refret...
Jun 2,  2024 Cut a piece of ebony to replace the broken corner. Hollowed out the recess a bit more so there is no pressure on the jack socket. Added 2 more holes for screws. Glued the pieces together, including the steel reinforcing plate. Started shaping the new piece.
Jun 3,  2024 Completed the repair to the Burns scratchplate and reassembled it. Had to take it apart again to clean the toggle switch, but now it works well.
Jun 4,  2024 Started enlarging the hole in the flute piece that joins the head and body. The hole is about 1inch in diameter and almost 3 inches deep. Probably could do it just with turning tools, but making a reamer and using that will be easier and less prone to disaster. Ordered some more HSS.
Jun 6,  2024 Cut a piece of brass for the tailstock bolt head. Drilled and tapped it to 14mm.
Jun 7,  2024 Turned a 14mm bolt to make a screw chuck adapter for the 4 jaw chuck. Started grinding the 25mm reamer for the hole in the piece between the head and body joints of the flute.
Jun 8,  2024 Completed grinding the 25mm reamer. I may have made the angle a little steeper than necessary. Started making a handle to drive it. The ones I already have are for 3mm HSS reamer blades, and this is 4mm. Cut a piece of 20mm steel rod for this. 20mm wont go into the headstock shaft bore so I will need to use the tailstock to support the free end when I turn it down for the threaded section. I had cut it too long to fit in the lathe, maximum it can handle when using the back centre is only about 5 inches. Had to remove about 1.5 inches. All set up ready to turn the end for the thread now.
Jun 9,  2024 Turned the 4mm reamer holder shank down and cut a thread on the last section.
Jun 10, 2024 Cut the square section that will locate in the handle. Filed the first flat, took about 600 strokes of the file. Cut the others with the hacksaw. Its good practice for accurate sawing and saves quite a lot of work.
Jun 11, 2024 Cut the slot for the blade. Used a hacksawfor the sides and the piercing saw with a fine blade to cut across the bottom. Managed to do it without breaking the blade or resorting to wobbling the waste piece to get it to separate. Still had to file a bit off the sides, but at least I have a file that will fit in the 4mm slot, unlike the earlier versions for 3mm reamer blades. For those I had had to use the HSS as a cold chisel.
Jun 12, 2024 Turned the wooden part of the reamer handle.
Jun 13, 2024 Turned the bolt head for the tailstock securing bolt. Fitted a piece of threaded rod and added some temporary handles using a 6mm countersunk machine screw and one of the handles from the broken tap driver. The brass head was all turned by hand mostly using the lilac handled graver. Also used the beading tool and the parting tool. It would be good to have a smaller beading tool but I'm not sure how I would cut it. It would need a very small mousetail file.
Jun 14, 2024 Started on the handles for the headstock securing bolt.
Jun 16, 2024 Completed the small handle.
Jun 17, 2024 Made some ferrules.
Jun 18, 2024 Completed the large handle for the tailstock securing bolt. Cut a piece of brass tube to make a sleeve for the toolrest securing bolt. Forgot to account for the wooden cross piece at the bottom so it was initially too long. Now I have a piece that will probably be perfect to replace the 4 washers on the large reamer. The toolrest is now easier to move around with one hand.
Jun 19, 2024 Hardened the large reamer handle and turned the piece of brass to replace the 4 washers.
Jun 20, 2024 Turned the inside of the joint piece of the flute. It was very slightly triangular (constant diameter) and probably a little small. It's now circular and 26mm diameter which will allow for 3mm tenon thickness in the head and body pieces. I turned it using the 1/4inch square scraper tool, while holding it in the 4 jaw chuck.
Jun 21, 2024 Made a carrier for the joint piece. I had hoped it would be stable enough held between a cup chuck and the tailstock but the joint piece rocks slightly and the carrier turned out to be very slightly eccentric. I think it may be partly because I used one of the larger cup chucks and it doesn't seat perfectly. Maybe I should stick with the brass cup chuck. Also I will try making a plug chuck and back centre as I did for the head joint. That way the bore can be supported at both ends and hopefully not rock.
Jun 25, 2024 Started making a new carrier which will fit in the brass cup chuck. Locates well and almost turned down to size.
Jun 26, 2024 Finished the carrier and started turning a piece for the backcentre to support the other end of the flute joint piece.
Jun 27, 2024 Completed the backcentre. I turned the outer end down to a close fit, then used that as a visual guide to turn the inner section down to the same size. Almost got it right first try, but I had left a smaller diameter section that fitted in a small cup chuck so I could skim it down to a perfect fit. Had to cut that off once it fitted, there is not enough room between the plug chuck and the back centre to keep it.
Jun 28, 2024 Made a ⅛inch beading tool
Jul 1,  2024 Made the handle for the beading tool. Hardenned and tempered the steel. Not sure the temper quite reached far enough. The straw colour may not have reached the tip. Lets see if it breaks in use.
Jul 2,  2024 Trued up the Outside of the flute joint section and marked it out for turning to shape.
Jul 3,  2024 Made a small ¼ circle ⅛inch lathe tool, including the handle, and hardening and tempering.
Jul 4,  2024 Turned the joint piece to its final profile. The beadings were easier than expected, although I did have a little trouble with breakout on the centre beading. The ¼ circle tool seems to work better than the beading tool, which is closer to a semi-circle. I might grind it back a little. I think the trapping effect of the 2 side points is not helpful. I had forgotten how tedious sanding can be...
Jul 5,  2024 Cut and rough turned a piece for the handle end of the head joint of the flute.
Jul 8,  2024 Cut a piece off the edge of some 30x4mm HSS to make a 25-28 reamer.
Jul 9,  2024 Ground the new reamer.
Jul 10, 2024 Drilled and reamed the piece for the handle end of the head joint.
Jul 16, 2024 Turned a carrier for the latest flute piece.
Jul 17, 2024 Turned the headjoint handle end piece and sanded it.
Jul 18, 2024 Turned the headjoint down to roughly the final size and fitted the handle end piece. Not glued yet, still considering what glue to use. There seems to be a flaw in the outer end, so I had to proceed extremely carefully. The obvious part is covered by the end piece so it should be ok.
Jul 19, 2024 Glued the handle end piece on and turned the tenon for the body end joint. Glued that on too.
Jul 22, 2024 Drilled the embouchure using the drill press on its fastest speed. Turned the headjoint to its final size and sanded it.
Jul 23, 2024 Turned the body down a little and turned the tenon to fit in the headjoint. There is a crack but it should be ok as this joint is to be glued.
Jul 24, 2024 Rough turned the extra stock for the handle and footjoint. Cut off a section for the handle and the footjoint. Turned the footjoint to fit the carrier and bored it out to ½ inch.
Jul 30, 2024 Tweaked the tenon at the head end of the body so it fits close against the shoulder without leaving an internal gap. Turned the footjoint end tenon to fit. Marked and drilled the fingerholes.c
Jul 31, 2024 Made a tuning knife from an offcut of the flute cane joint pieces and a short length of ¼inch silver steel.
Aug 1,  2024 Sharpened the tuning knife and used it to undercut the holes. It works much better on the smaller holes. I will need to make another larger one. Turned the flute body down to size and sanded it.
Aug 2,  2024 Made the metal part of the new tuning knife. Turned down the end of the old flat drill and cut a thread on it in preparation for fitting a handle.
Aug 3,  2024 Made the handle for the new tuning knife. Hardened and tempered the steel part, and fitted the handle. Sharpened it.
Aug 4,  2024 Made a handle for the old flat drill. Marked out the tail end of the drill for filing it square using the index holes on the back of the 4 jaw chuck.
Aug 5,  2024 Squared off the tail end of the old flat drill and fitted the handle. Turned the foot mortice a bit deeper and turned the tenon to fit perfectly.
Aug 6,  2024 cleaned up the headstock pulley boss a little, turning it in place. Started cutting a piece of brass for the index plate. Cut the first quarter with the piercing saw and fret saw using the coarser blades (about 16tpi). Managed to break one so I tried using the hacksaw. Turns out the hacksaw will cut a curve of this radius (just).
Aug 7,  2024 Finished cutting out the brass disk for the indexing plate. Made a faceplate. Already had the brass boss, cut the wooden disk and fitted the boss.
Aug 8,  2024 Trued up the faceplate. Started investigating layout methods for marking the holes in the indexing disc.
Aug 9,  2024 Marked out and drilled 5 holes in the indexing disc. Mounted it on the faceplate. The centre mark ended up very slightly off centre. Cleaning it up and recentering the mark was not easy. A small hole would be fine, but a centre point is difficult to turn. Got there close enough with a combination of abrasive paper and the very small graver. It might have been easier just to rely on the circular scratch marks to define the centre. It is only needed for marking out the radial lines. The circles will be done using the lathe.
Aug 12, 2024 Marked out the 24 hole ring on the indexing disc. Blacked out the extra lines in preparation for marking out the 36 hole ring.
Aug 13, 2024 Marked out the 36 hole ring. I made a tomahawk trisection tool out of a piece of clear plastic that came from a pack of individual butter pieces and used it to divide each 60° angle into 3. There appeared to be a tiny discrepancy in some of the 60° angles, as the tomahawk didn't always sit at exactly the same radius. It's interesting considering how to mark things like this out accurately. Getting a "second opinion" seems valuable, ie trisecting opposite angles and looking for inaccuracies by comparing them using the centre of the circle as a reference point. Marked out the 14 hole ring using a different method. This time I did the preparation on paper, marking a line with 7 equal steps and using the second mark to find the intersection of the circumference with the end of the first side of a pentagon. Steping the length of the side around the circle gives the angles. Scribing the same diameter circle on the brass and stepping the side length around the circumference gives the angles which can then be projected onto the circle with the desired diameter. Using the centre and each vertex and projecting the line back to the opposite side of the circle gives the other 7 points.
Aug 16, 2024 Marked out the 26 hole ring. This one was a bitch. Had to divide a circle into 13, and that is a lot of steps to multiply any error. It took many goes at stepping around the circle, which I did on paper. Then I doubled that up by starting from the opposite end of the diameter. That gave me 3 points for every diameter I needed to merk, and a chance to spot any errors. There were some which I tweaked.  Once that was right I tried marking out the circle on the brass disc, but still needed a few tries to get the distance to step around the circle right.
Aug 17, 2024 Marked out the 10 hole ring using the same method as the 26 hole ring. Punched the 26 and 10 hole rings and drilled them all. Turned out the centre and started to clean up the burrs ready for fitting to the pulley.
Aug 18, 2024 Finished cleaning up the burrs on the back of the index plate. The hole was a fraction too small so I had to re-chuck it and open it out. # times. Each time meant dismantling the headstock bearings and shaft. Fits nicely and is screwwed on in place ready for final cleanup.
Aug 19, 2024 Cleaned up the dividing plate, sanded it to 1000. Cut the shape of the rear bearing adjuster wingnut.
Aug 20, 2024 Turned down the foot joint a bit and marked out the various features on it.
Aug 21, 2024 Turned the main diameter of the foot joint down leaving the various beadings square.
Aug 22, 2024 Established the features of the foot joint. The lower part is close to final size but the key mount part still needs to be reduced further.
Aug 23, 2024 Reduced the keymount part further.
Aug 27, 2024 Drilled the key hole and the side vent hole. Realised I had missread the plans, and what I thought were hole sizes were actually the inside end of the undercutting. This means I will need to bush every hole as they are all too large, including the embouchure. Adjusted the mouldings on the foot joint and sanded it. The bottom 2 notes are within reach of where they should be.
Aug 28, 2024 Found a piece to make the hole inserts. Resharpened the rip saw and cut a long square. Started turning it round ready for the inserts.
Aug 30, 2024 Drilled out the flute holes a little, so that the sides were parallel (I had started undercutting them when testing the tuning knives). Turned inserts for each and glued them in place (superglue). Cleaned up inside and outside. Outside was easy, but inside was a little tricky. Considered making a long chisel out of a piece of 14mm round steel bar, but ended up using the reamers, and carefully controlling the depth so I could scrape away at the upstream end of each plug. Alowing the reamer to enter even a fraction of a millimter too far would cause the reamer to stick against the side of the plug. Had to be really careful. Any force aplied would risk loosening a plug.
Aug 31, 2024 Drilled the fingerholes again. Started at 3.5mm and used a small file to make adjustments so the holes were concentric with the plugs. Drilled every hole to the nearest drill size below the specified size. Tried playing it and it is almost ok. Some of the 3rd octave is not there or not right.
Sep 1,  2024 Started opening up the tone holes and undercutting them. The angled tuning knife is the only one small enough to do the smaller holes, and it is not so easy to use. Made a small straight tuning knife from a broken 5mm drill.
Sep 2,  2024 Did some more tuning.
Sep 3,  2024 Made the handle piece.
Sep 5,  2024 Made a 4mm tuning knike, and fitted a handle to the 3.5mm drill bit with the bent shank.
Sep 6,  2024 Designed and made the key for the flute.
Sep 9,  2024 Cut the slot for the key and fitted it. Drilling was tricky, couldn't work out a way to do it with precision, just had to guess and do it mostly by eye. Drilled the wood straight through, then drilled one side of the key. Pinned that side and drilled the other side of the key. Filed the excess off the key boss so it rotates on the pin ok. Seems to have worked out.
Sep 10, 2024 Added a spring and a pad to the key. Had to redo it and it still isn't working great. The bottom D is there but sometimes need to press on the key. It may bed in with time and I have left it with extra pressure from a hair band to help that.
Sep 11, 2024 Key is working a little better, and I can see the imprint of the hole in the leather. Sanded the head and foot sections again. It wont be so easy to do once the pieces are glued together.
Sep 13, 2024 glued the sections together. Found some more spring steel that is double the thickness of the current spring. Will use that to make a new spring if the key doesn't work right. Need to wait and see. I think it will improve more with time (and oiling?)
Sep 14, 2024 Marked out a long section of 14mm rod for a reamer holder.
Sep 16, 2024 Cut the slot for the reamer blades, drilled and tapped holes for the screws. tried using it held in the vice, but it is not so easy and a little too short. Turned a 10 section on the end and threaded it and marked out and started cutting the square for a handle.
Sep 17, 2024 Finished cutting the square and made a handle. Used the indexing wheel to mark out 10 sides on the centre section and planed them flat. Fitted the handle.
Sep 18, 2024 Oiled the bore of the flute.
Sep 19, 2024 tried tuning the flute. High f is proving dificult to get. Pushing the cork out makes it work, but it is still very flat.
Sep 20, 2024 Played the flute some more. Either it is geting better or I am getting used to it. Still not easy to hit the lowest note fast. Needs very precise positioning, and the size of it is tending to either move the embouchure out of alignment or partially uncover the lowest hole. Got to stretch...
Sep 21, 2024 Cleared the bench to try fixing the 12 string. Will attempt glueing it in place first, and if that fails, remove the neck and rebuild the heel.
Sep 23, 2024 Drilled the end plug of the flute and tapped it for the hammer head insert that will be the boot. Filed and sanded the key. Replaced the spring with a thicker one. Replaced the pad, skin surface down this time. Getting the lowest note was getting easier, even with the weak spring and the pad skin side up. Only remaining problem is that high F natural (12-45--). It sounds well enough but is so flat it is almost the same as the high E (12--567)
Sep 24, 2024 Glued the heel of the 12-string. Used a sash cramp clamped in the vice to provide downward pressure. More experiments with the walking stick flute. Still having trouble with f'''# but the tone is getting really nice.
Sep 26, 2024 Fitted a piece of water pipe to the bike so I can carry the flute stick.
Sep 27, 2024 Finished turning the foot of the flute stick. It was a little large and had a longtitudonal convex curve that didn't look quite right. Discovered a crack in the head where the handle fits. Considering how best to fix it. Probably pinning will do it. If not I might need to add a brass ring.
Sep 28, 2024 Reconsiderd fixing the crack. Replacing the final beading with a brass ring makes more sense. The flute is longer than the lathe bed though. Planning a lathe bed extension. It would need to be 12 inches to use the tailstock, but I could use the carrier on a shorter extension, maybe 4-6 inches. This could just be 2 blocks with a hole for the bolts that currently secure the bedways to the frame, with longer bolts to go through the extension.
Sep 29, 2024 Rethink of the lathe extension, something bolted to the top ill be easier and quicker. This is probably best as a temporary fixture with re-useable parts. Located a piece for the main bar.
Sep 30, 2024 Planed the extension piece to thickness and width, located a piece for the upright.
